Perry Ellis International's (PERY) CEO Oscar Feldenkreis on Q4 2017 Results - Earnings Call Transcript | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Perry Ellis International's (PERY) CEO Oscar Feldenkreis on Q4 2017 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptMar.22.17 | About: Perry Ellis (PERY) Perry Ellis International, Inc. (NASDAQ:PERY)
Q4 2017 Earnings Conference Call
March 22, 2017 09:00 ET
Executives
George Feldenkreis - Executive Chairman
Oscar Feldenkreis - President & CEO
David Rattner - CFO
Analysts
Eric Beder - Wunderlich
Ronald Bookbinder - Coker & Palmer
Greg Pendy - Sidoti & Company
Ed Yruma - KeyBanc Capital Markets
Operator
Good morning, ladies and gentlemen, and welcome to Perry Ellis International's Fiscal Year 2017 Fourth Quarter and Year End Earnings Results Conference. As a reminder, today's conference is being recorded.
Before we begin, I would like to remind you that some of the comments made on the call, either as part of the prepared remarks or in response to your questions, may contain forward-looking statements that are made pursuant to the Safe Harbor provisions of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. Such information is subject to risks and uncertainties as described in the press release and in documents that we have filed with the SEC.
Joining us today for this call from Perry Ellis are George Feldenkreis, Executive Chairman of the company; Oscar Feldenkreis, Chief Executive Officer and President; and David Brettner, Chief Financial Officer; and Anita Britt who is assisting with the transition of the CFO office and is an additional resource to answer any questions.
It is my pleasure to now turn the call over to Mr. George Feldenkreis. Please go ahead, sir.
George Feldenkreis
Good morning. We've got to report on a good year for Perry Ellis International. We completed the rationalization of our brand portfolio and we are now fully focused on our core global branch. With numerous microeconomic issues affecting the apparel industry in the United States and worldwide, we are pleased to report that our core wholesale business increased by 1.6% or 3.2% on a constant currency basis.
Through our management of payment coupled with a strong product performance, we delivered an adjusted growth margin of 37.2%, a 440 basis points ahead of last year. We will continue focusing on our goal to drive our gross margin to 40% over the next few years. We've managed SG&A very well despite rising cost and overhead and trends, allowing us to report on adjusted EBITDA margin of 6.6% for the fiscal year and 8.4% for our fourth quarter.
With this back drop, we are confident to project an increase in revenues for fiscal 2018 to a range of $870 million to $880 million in revenues. We are projecting our revenue guidance for the year in the range of adjusted earnings per share of $2.07 to $2.17, which represent an increase over adjusted last year EPS.
It is why we think this is very achievable. We are concentrated, we focus approach to our various global core brand and businesses which are Perry Ellis, Original Penguin, [indiscernible] and the women brand. Oscar will inform you about the performance future of those businesses.
We have developed a very diversified customer base that can achieve solid results despite the fact that some of our business partners have experienced their decline. We all know that the department store business have been challenged. While department store business represent approach in nearly 25% of our business, we think that the tailored have taken the right step to rationalize their store base and clothes on the performing door.
We are also upholding the changes that the tailored are making to receive flaws ensuring that goods are in the selling floor when customers are shopping -- thereby driving fast returns and reduced markdowns. This will provide a more level flow for our quarterly reporting, as well on a quarter-by-quarter basis. At the same time we are intensifying our distribution through other third party ecommerce partners, specially the distribution, as well as through our international network which remains very underdeveloped.

Generally speaking, we believe that the new reduced retail space in America is a positive development in the long run, especially in light of the way which retail is moving these days and the demographic implication of generation Z, generation Y versus generation X. This alphabets of generations are really creating a no-paradigm which manufactures [indiscernible] have to learn to navigate if they want to succeed.
From a working capital perspective, we were able to reduce our inventory to $151 million compared to $103 million on the end of last year. This is our lowest inventory in the last six years. Strategic reduction on inventory allows to drive more profitable top line and allow your company to enter the new fiscal year in a very healthy condition.
Needless to say, we're extremely proud of the progress we continue to make toward our near and long term objective. The national business will continue to be very bullish in the United Kingdom as well as in Europe, Mexico and Canada. We feel that once we get a better idea of how Brexit will develop, business in the UK will increase considerably, while at the same time will continue to increase our business in the continent.
As strategic decreases of our multi-brand distribution in the Europe and the UK is paying out, we are now managing six brands which gives us a lot of runway to grow. Brands are Original Penguin, Farah Vintage, Farah Classic, Callaway, Ben Hogan and most recently Nike Swim. Nike Swim has had a very strong sales through in the few channels where we delivered this year. We expect this to be a great growth opportunity for the company in the future. We feel that in the next few years, our Nike Swim will be $100 million-business and have the potential to grow further as Nike Corporation extends our distribution territories.
On the retail of direct-to-consumer front which bidding [ph] sales declined more notably in our full price stores and some market. You'll recall two years ago we announced that we will be closing stores that are no longer profitable. Much of that profitability was lost because of rent increases by small operators. We're happy to report that last year, we closed 10 stores, six Penguin stores and four Perry outlets. These closed stores have revenue of $4.7 million last year.
Of that store contribution was a minus $1.2 million. We are now planning on closing five additional store that had revenues of $2.7 million last year and lost $700,000. After this five closing, we have 10 stores remaining that generate a negative furor [ph] of those will be closed in the next two years and consequently will return our retail businesses' strong profitability if not before then.
By the end of the year, we project to have 65 stores in the United States and we intend to continue opening stores with a more selective approach in an area where rents are commensurate with the potential revenue that these stores could generate in such sense. On the licensing front, we've completed another successful year, adding 22 new licensees to our seven of our branch. Organic revenue increased by 6.2% and is steadily growing. Licensing continues to make a strong contribution to our operating performance.
Our licensing team remains focused on new markets and categories for our programs as well as targeted opportunities for our license-only brand in addition to the strong pipeline of new project. We fully expect that the strategic growth of our direct business international will generate a national expansion of lives in business as we leverage the brand equity of our portfolio of brands.
We will continue to focus on what we do best among other things, global sourcing. We have great overseas organization that we just initiated in the production to engineering project or ERP. This project will allow us to reduce considerably time from product conception to store delivery. Process also involved working together with our business partners to achieve those results. Retailored are realizing of the currencies [indiscernible] in advance is no longer working and design will be done much closer to the delivery dates.

Very good competitor like Zara, H&M, et cetera have succeeded in this strategy of real-stint to market. American retailer most adapt such methodology or it will be impossible for them to compete with worthy competitors. We're investing in a new warehouse management system and reengineering and distribution centered to drive better efficiencies and to reduce our SGIA. We'll also continue to lower our sourcing cost by consolidating some of our overseas offices.
We believe that we are a very strong company. Unfortunately, some brand and some players in the industry have experienced major difficulties. Some of it the consequence of over-paying for brands have product equity group over-paying for business in the last few years while not having the proper management in place. By 2020, it is estimated that generation Y, those born in the 1990s or early 1990s will represent 30% of the retail business.
We continue to look at the future with confidence while we continue to build our brand that resonate with the younger generation of consumers, such as Original Penguin, Cubavera, Gione [ph], and especially Nike at the same time through our increased marketing activity, we keep our current followings happy while we work to bring in new customers. Our strategies have worked very well in the last couple of years and it has allowed us to establish a strong foothold in different channel, different geographies and different products.
We're very proud of our financial condition, it is strongest in 20 years. For fiscal 2017, the company performance and working capital discipline generated $42 million in operating cash flow or $2.78 per share, resulting in a historical low net debt to capitalization of 17.2%. We have a very strong balance sheet ready for future growth in both the United States as well as international. Your company is in great shape.
I will now turn the call over to Oscar.
Oscar Feldenkreis
Thanks, George. Good morning, to all in joining us on the call. First, I'd like to welcome David Rattner to the management team. He comes with a wealth of consumer product experience spending over 20 years at Elizabeth Arden. I look forward to his contribution to the company.
The fourth quarter marks our 13th quarter executed under our 5-point growth in profitability plan. We have made solid progress towards the objectives of focusing on our core lifestyle brands, which generated solid expansions in growth margin, EBITDA margins for the quarter and full year.
As it relates to revenues, our core brands performed well in total. Our revenues for the quarter trailed the prior year has increased conversions on our retail stores was offset by traffic declines driven by softness in the overall environment and we had a $12 million-shift in shipments to week-1 of fiscal 2018 due to retailers request. We completed the exit of over 30 brands and $100 million in revenues over the last three years, positioning us well to focus on our core global brands in the years ahead.
We continue to focus on the international expansion which is a 5% on a constant currency basis representing 14% of the total revenues. Our balance sheet ended the year in a very solid position with the strongest credit metrics we have seen in the company's history. Fiscal 2017 capped the year of outstanding inventory management with levels turning just about 4x per year and down 17% over prior year end. This will continue to be a key focal point for us for the years ahead.
The year included solid progress towards implementing initiatives that we believe positioned us possibly for the dynamic shifts in how consumers are shopping today. Focus on differentiated brand with a strong heritage and innovative qualities and accelerating their shift online. On both fronts, we believe we are set up to win.

We have positioned ourselves very well for the increase in focus on digital and ecommerce growth. While making the right investments over the last three years, we now serviced direct in third party ecommerce from design through fulfillment internally and have grown to represent 8% of our total revenue base.
Investments in cutting edge marketing technology platforms such as dynamic personalization, CRM driven segmentations and omni-channel attribution equips us to better drive our direct as well as our customer ecommerce business. Using CRM to build new prospecting segments throughout our digital marketing activities coupled with our customer-based loyalty programs have driven increased results across [indiscernible] in our target audience.
Another critical factor to our success has been an unwavering focus on evolving new products to meet the lifestyle needs of the consumer today. We have combined this focus with a steadfast discipline in our supply chain. We continue to make in-roads in forwarding our R&D capabilities into product coupled with providing a faster process and turn to that we can be proactive in design innovations and convert to the on-floor product. We are implementing new technologies in 3D design which will produce our process time as well as sampling cost.
With that said, we are operating in a global world where change is constant, consumers are demanding brands and product excellence and companies need to be both proactive adapters and agile in their execution. I'd like to touch on some of our key performance statistics for the quarter and I hope to leave you as excited as I am with our business initiatives.
Perry Ellis, we have heard from many of our retail partners that men's apparel was one of the top performing areas for the quarter. Our third party ecommerce continue to be the star of all distribution zones. We implement a new marketing initiative with many of our partners to increase the focus and investments around digital. This will ensure that we drive brand awareness through social media outlets which we believe will broaden the appeal.
From a product perspective, the units we delivered performed well. Driven by innovative technical fabrics with performance enhancing stretch, wicking [ph] properties as well as stain resistance in easy-care features. We also continue to benefit from our increase in wearing our fabrications which our consumers are looking for.
As we move through fiscal '18, we see performance attributes being a strong theme from a washable suit to our performance pants. We are not only maintaining our strong innovation flow, but also ensuring our enhancements, our top of mind with consumers through marketing campaigns and point of sale communications. And our expectations from the positive performance in men's to continue our support by a positive initial response to our transitional spring deliveries.
Most impactful is the consumers buying new units that he can wear immediately. This is driving a shift in our flow of goods to customers, ranging up to three weeks later to target the selling through our versus last year. We're excited by the change as we will provide a more even flow of shipments by quarters, making Q2 and Q3 more impactful. We also believe this will result in faster turn over on lower mark downs as our good reside on the selling floor for less time.
Original Penguin. Our fourth quarter for Original Penguin was solid. Our retail despite a lower shipments overall given our focus on reducing access inventory to alleviate the prominence of the brand. The strategy continues to be a successful one as evidenced by Original Penguin driving the largest percentage of our licensing gain for the year with five new agreements across the U.S., Europe, Canada and South Africa. We believe this brand is one of the largest opportunities for the future growth. Our priorities for OPG in fiscal 2018 are to increase specialties to our distribution, as well as ecommerce and as we look to partner with retailers that we believe enhances the cool factor of the Original Penguin brand. We are energized by the strength of the brand's direction and positioning.

Our leadership position in Golf apparel continues to be driven by product innovation and technology. During the quarter end year, this led to a solid increase in our core golf brands at wholesale and retail. Our technology-infused product assortments help ensure our customers be well-prepared to handle the temperature ranges in Q4 from cold to warm. This new innovative product led to strong performances in our lightweight layering programs, elements and weather series as well as in our optitherm series which has a thermal insulation, stretch, water and wind resistance.
Warm weather climatic zones benefited from our Motion Flow 360 stretch, mitts coupled with new expandable wait band bottoms and lightweight water repelling shorts which also drove solid sales. In fiscal 2018, our core golf business will continue to expand in distribution with key specialty retailers. The Callaway brand has taken on a more focused approach to grow our revenues and market share within the authentic golf channel. We will expand our growth to include Golf Galaxy, PGA Tour, super stores, Academy and Golfhound, just to name a few, as well as other fine golf courses.
As we see Europe as a continued growth opportunity for the Callaway brand today, we service all of Europe in more than 2,500 to 3,000 doors in the authentic channel. We're also excited about our Jack Nicklaus brand launch with Target set for second quarter. We feel that this is an excellent opportunity for Target to showcase a world-class brand with top-notch lifestyle products. We plan to launch in 1,650 doors, as well as an online for the summer of 2017.
AS you know, fourth quarter is a key period for the swim season. Our Nike Swim business return to a solid performance. We were very pleased not only with North America, but the initial early reads in our new markets of latter America and Europe. We are pleased with our international expansion and see more growth to come. In fact, at year end, approximately 13% of our business was represented outside of the USA.
As we look to spring, we believe we are positioned well as early indicators across all genders have been positive both online and in-store. Encouraging trend shows solid interest in women's, which is a major growth category to complement our men's business. Our product initiatives and stretch, swim fronts, UV protection and tops, dry fit and hydro tees are off to a strong start for the season. Equally exciting is our launch into key retailers in Europe including ASOS, Next, El Corte Inglés, JD Sports as well as swim specialty stores.
Turning to women's sportswear. While women's sportswear was a very challenging zone in the fourth quarter, we believe the Rafaella performed better than most branded businesses. Newness in our new fashion deliveries, coupled with our new denim which benefits launch in the third quarter were key drivers. Performance attributes including stretch and textured fabrication resonated well. As we are transitioning into spring products, we are pleased with our initial selling, which incorporates collections that bridge consumers' needs for the career into casual and we're also taking advantage of the undeserved plus size consumers which expanded our product offering.
Laundry saw success in the fourth quarter driven by holiday occasion dressings. As we look to fiscal 2018, we are expanding doors with key upscale retailers which is critical to the success of the brand. We are equally pleased by the strengthening of laundry online and are driving digital investments to continue the upward momentum.
We believe we have the key elements to support our business platforms. To continue our successful growth domestically and internationally and to further drive profitability gains, we have a more focused business pattern, we have solid momentum in many of our core brands and businesses at the start of the year and are particularly excited about the core strength of our men's wear business the new roll outs within Nike International and the golf lifestyle expansions into target with a highly talented team, strong lifestyle brands and initiatives in place to generate domestic and international sales growth at increased margins rate, we feel we are very well-positioned to achieve our guidance and move towards our longer term profitability goals.

I'd like to turn over the call to David Rattner.
David Rattner
Thank you, Oscar. Good morning, everyone. I'd like to begin by thanking Anita for the strong leadership she has provided to this organization. The company have benefited from her expertise and she has inspired people all across the organization with our passion for the business. I am truly excited to join the Perry Ellis team.
In the six weeks I have been with the company, I have met with the majority of our operating area and I'm delighted to be working with the company that not only has powerful brands, but also a strong infrastructure and an abundance of great talent across the organization. I am keenly focused on adding value in guiding the business from a finance perspective, but also keeping a very diligent eye on infrastructure discipline, as well as a very healthy balance sheet in support of our future growth plans.
Turning to the quarter, as outlined in the release, we discussed the challenges that we saw in the quarter which hindered our fourth quarter top line growth. Certainly, the team has been prevalent across the industry in the consumer space. With that said, we did perform very well on our core businesses as evidence by our healthy gross margin and tight inventory levels. I believe it's important to point out that for the year, we realized a solid 1.6% increase or 3.2% in constant currency in our core men's businesses.
Detracting from this growth were our planned exits in reductions in the challenging traffic at retail during the second half of December and January which we could not control. While we solidly converted more customers once they were in our stores, the traffic delta of mid-single digit declines in the first few quarters of the year to a 15% decline in Q4 was a huge obstacle to overcome.
The traffic trends also impacted our flow at year end with retailers once again looking to receipt later in their warehouse than the original plan. With that shift, we ended up shipping $12 million of goods in the first week of February from the original plan of January. Let me run you through our segments for the year. Revenue in our men's sportswear and swim segment totaled $625 million as compared to $641 million in prior year. Increases were noted in our Perry Ellis, Golf Lifestyle apparel and Nike Swim businesses. This growth was offset by business exit and the negative impact of foreign currency translation.
Revenue in our women's sportswear segment totaled $108 million, as compared to $127 million in the year ago period. Solid shipment growth within the department store channel was offset by reduction in special markets in [indiscernible] shipment, driven by a higher level of available goods in the marketplace.
Direct-to-consumer revenue totaled $92 million as compared to $97 million in the prior year. Comparable sales decreased by 1.7% for the year and 6.2% for the fourth quarter. Bump traffic was down 9.5% for the year and 15% for the fourth quarter. On a positive note, we converted stronger 50 basis points for the year and 125 basis points for the fourth quarter. By managing a sharper assortment in store, we kept comp margin through the year at plus 1% and down 3.8% for the fourth quarter.
Licensing revenues total $36 million, up $1.3 million as compared to $34.7 million in the prior year. This area of our business benefited from new agreements with the remainder driven by the strength of our core licenses for Perry Ellis and Original Penguin.
Moving on to total company results beginning with the adjusted gross margin, gross margin exceeded expectations as outlined in our release with fourth quarter gross margin expanding 150 basis points and full year 2017 gross margin expanding 140 basis points. The critical drivers for the quarter and for the year had been diligent inventory management, coupled with strong product focus which has driven stronger merchandising margins and solid retail performance.

Somewhat offsetting this expansion, foreign exchange negatively impacted gross margin by 40 basis points for the year and 50 basis points for the quarter. We have countered by taking strategic price increases where appropriate. We have also seen currencies moderate against the dollar and expect to see less pressure on gross margin from currency in the second half of fiscal 2018.
Adjusted SG&A totaled $62 million for the quarter as compared to $67 million in the prior year period. Full year SG&A totaled $263 million as compared to $267 million in fiscal 2016. During the year, we realized $6 million in SG&A savings, driven by reductions across our corporate structure and well as in more strategic sample productivity in numerous other areas.
Turning to the balance sheet. Inventories ended the year in-line with our guidance of $151 million, down 17% from $183 million reported in prior year. Not only our inventory very tight, but aged goods are the lowest they have been as the percentage of inventory in five years. Turns expanded to just under four times for the year as well. Our operating performance coupled with inventory discipline enabled us to generate $42 million in operating cash flow for the year and continue to improve our coverage ratios. Our strong balance sheet puts us in great position to continue our global expansion in our key businesses.
Turning to fiscal 2018, the landscape continues to evolve. Retailers are becoming more focused on driving profitable sales in closing for core performing real estate. As seen during the recent holiday season, consumer focus on digital is gaining serious traction with not only the millennials, but with other generations including the baby boomers. Price is important to most consumers, but must be accompanied by quality and great fashion.
Our company is positioned exceptionally well to address these changing dynamics. We are leaders with our retail partners maximizing productivity of our ongoing stores by focusing on product, merchandise assortment and investing in digital asset.
As fiscal year 2018 is under way, we are excited about the future year. We entered the year with our retail partners having very clean stock levels. We have completed the heavy lifting of our brand and business exits executed over the last three years and our core businesses are performing well. Our forward revenue guidance for the year of $870 million to $880 million incorporates the carryover of $12 million in retailer shipments from Q4 and core growth of almost 2% or $15 million.
Our revenue guidance also incorporates a $7 million negative impact from foreign exchange principally in first half of the year as we anniversary the Brexit impact to the pound in July. We are planning direct-to-consumer even for the year as store exits are expected to offset healthy growth in ecommerce.
Driving our $15 million revenue growth expectation are the new introduction of Jack Nicolas Golf Apparel into Target, Nike Golf introductions into Europe and Latin America, as well as new introductions in Canada for Original Penguin, Golf and Perry Ellis. While we expect to see further growth, we believe it is prudent to remain curious with our guidance given the back drop of stored closures that continued to be announced.
Gross margins are expected to expand to approximate 37.3% to 37.5%. We continue to expect the same drivers of inventory management and product performance to position us to achieve this improvement. While not factored into our guidance, we do see opportunity for gross margin expansion in our international business in Europe as we take price increases beginning in fall 2017 to offset currency.
SG&A is expected to decrease to 30.3% to 30.5% of revenue from 30.6% of revenue in fiscal 2017. We expect EBITDA margin to increase in the range of 6.7% to 7%; depreciation and amortization should range $14.7 million to $14.9 million and interest ranging from $7.6 million to $8 million. Interest assumes the fed will step in another two to three times before year end. Our tax rate is expected to approximate 15% and shares are expected to increase slightly to a range of $15.3 million to $15.4 million. We see earnings per share ranging from $2.07 to $2.17 for the year. Finally, operating cash flow is expected to approximate $2 per share with capital expenditures approximating $15 million to $16 million.

As we look at the quarterly flow, Oscar has mentioned the reflow of goods by our retail partners to rebalance Q2, Q3 and Q4. We see approximately a three-week reflow which will decrease Q1 revenues by $41 million, but increase Q2 by $10 million, Q3 by $20 million and Q4 by $10 million. Therefore we expect Q1 revenues to range from $230 million to $235 million. We expect Q1 EPS in a range of $0.70 to $0.75 per share. Obviously with the reflow to the remaining quarters, we expect to see most quarters expanding in revenues and EPS.
In closing, while I'm new to the company, my goal over the next 100 days is to enhance our strategy with a focus on growth, optimal resource allocation, expense management and value creation. There is a lot of energy in the teams under George and Oscar and I am focused on identifying and implementing initiatives to make it even more efficient in the near future.
With that, I will turn the call over to the operator for Q&A.
Question-and-Answer Session
Operator
Thank you. [Operator Instructions] And we'll take our first question from Eric Beder from Wunderlich. Please go ahead.
Eric Beder
Good morning. Congratulations on a great end of the year.
David Rattner
Thank you.
Oscar Feldenkreis
Thank you, Eric.
Eric Beder
When you look at some of the new issues here, for Target, what products are you offering there in terms of categories and is this your first time significant in Target?
Oscar Feldenkreis
We tested with them in Q3 -- some product that was this small golf collection under the Nicklaus brand and it was very, very successful and going into the Q2, we'll be shipping them a full collection that will include shorts and tops. It's our first entry into the store side. We have been doing swim wear with them -- ladies swimwear online only for the last couple of years and this is a new introduction in being able to develop a branded business with Target stores both in stores and online. But we're very excited about the opportunities going forward.
Eric Beder
In terms of the debt, you have that $50 million high yield piece of paper. I believe after April, you can call that at par. What are you assuming in your projections with that and what should longer term the debt levels be for you?
David Rattner
I'll take that one. This is David. As you know, we've done a solid job of generating strong operating cash flow, approximately $128 million over the last three years. Approximately $46 million was redeployed into capital including brand shops that have driven stronger gross margins across our businesses. We expect to generate another $2 per share in operating cash flow this year. Our immediate focus is to invest in our international businesses as well as our core menswear brands. We have also been opportunistic with share repurchases and have $9 million remaining under the authorized plan. We will continue to evaluate and purchase where appropriate. Last and very important, we have spoken about calling the remainder of our $50 million senior notes which mature in April 2019. We are taking a hard look at this which seems like an easy decision, but with much uncertainty around global, economic and political decisions coming down the road, we want to be prudent and we'll make the determination after the first half of fiscal 2018. So, stay tuned on this one.
Eric Beder
I get that your answer is you're not assuming anything in the estimates being changed in the capital structure?
David Rattner
It's not in the guidance.
Eric Beder
Okay. All right, guys, congrats and good luck on 2017 year.
Oscar Feldenkreis
Thank you, Eric. Thank you for everything.
Operator
And we'll go next to Ronald Bookbinder from Coker & Palmer. Please go ahead.
Ronald Bookbinder
Ah. Good morning and congratulations also on a very nice quarter.

Oscar Feldenkreis
Thanks, Ron.
Ronald Bookbinder
On Target, you guys entered Wal-Mart a number of years ago with the Ben Hogan brand. What kind of revenues were you doing with Wal-Mart in golf beforehand and what kind of revenues does Ben Hogan do today? Such that we can sort of see the opportunity with Target.
Oscar Feldenkreis
Wal-Mart is currently today worldwide, about a $50 million business.
Ronald Bookbinder
And it was basically a zero beforehand?
Oscar Feldenkreis
It was zero when we opened the brand. Basically we built it up with them and it's Canada, Europe and the United States and it's a full collection of product.
Ronald Bookbinder
And on golf, you guys have done a terrific job of building out your golf business. It's primarily shirts though and historically, your company has a very strong men's bottoms business. Is there an opportunity to build out a golf pant business? Not just shorts, but a golf pant business with the new fabric technologies that are out there?
Oscar Feldenkreis
Yes. Just to clarify, paying golf, we do men's and ladies and 30% of our business today is ups to bottoms ratio. So 70% to 65% tops, to 30% to 35% bottoms. That includes shorts and pants as well and we also do wind wear and fleece. So it's a full lifestyle collection that is available 12 months out of the year. And there's a lot of excitement going on in bottoms today because the bottoms business has been reengineered with expandable waist bands, new technologies. Also, stretch has played such an important role for the consumer to go out and replenish their wardrobe by buying stretch in their garments.
Ronald Bookbinder
On the stores, you were going to close more stores than you have. You sort of reset that after the landlords became more realistic. Do you regret now as we look at these comp figures from Q4 and the traffic trends? Are some of those stores that ended up being able to renegotiate the leases? Do you somewhat regret having those stores or how should we think about the store growth going forward?
George Feldenkreis
We identified the necessity to close stores before a lot of much bigger people announced it last year. In that sense, whatever would be negotiated, it was on the basis that the stores will be profitable. But we closed 10 stores last year and there's already one that we closed the year before. That's a big number when you're thinking that sale of 12% of our store. We're going to be closing the one-third -- decided when we close this year. We have another group and this has expired in '18 and '19 and those were big stores, too. If they don't improve, obviously, the traffic improved on our retail knowledge of the business improved, we're using all kind of system, et cetera, et cetera, to try to build traffic also in the marketing side. But in the final analysis, depending on what is the traffic in the center as some of the centers also are closing the big anchored tenant, it will act like everybody in that center. We have to be very careful now in omitting in retail, especially with some of the -- the trend is now that A&B super centers are going to be open and the CMDs are not. If you happen to be in a center that's not A&B, you have a very large percentage of probability that you will not be making money and if you're in A&B, the more developers are trying to balance their loss of income by increasing their rents on the A&B. That's why so many specialty store business are going out of business.
Ronald Bookbinder
Okay. The inventory is so tight right now and a nice [indiscernible] doing great. But how should we think about yearend inventory for fiscal '18?
David Rattner
Yes, this is David. I'll take that one. Our discipline on inventory management will be driven and focus throughout this year. Our inventory should be even at $150 million to $160 million range at year end. So it will be relatively stable year-on-year.

Ronald Bookbinder
Okay, great. Thank you very much and good luck in the new year.
David Rattner
Thank you.
Oscar Feldenkreis
Thank you, Rob.
Operator
And we'll go next to Greg Pendy from Sidoti. Please go ahead.
Greg Pendy
Hey, guys. Thanks for taking my call and congratulations on a good quarter. Just wanted to touch on the top line guidance and just how do you guys were thinking about coming up with that number and just given the fact that a lot of your competitors have a much larger store flick print. How they've pulled back on what they're shipping into that channel and whether that could create any wide space opportunities for you?
Oscar Feldenkreis
Can you repeat your question, please?
Greg Pendy
Yes. Just going into your guidance on the top line revenue for the year and just whether you've been seeing any pockets where a lot of the competitors have pulled back what they're shipping into that channel and whether that could create any opportunities.
Oscar Feldenkreis
We're always looking for opportunities in wide space and the great thing is that we're very focused today in our brand portfolio, but there is opportunity still today out there of course in-store and online. Our authoritative position within our brands portfolios today with Original Penguin, Perry Ellis and our golf business allows us to take market share as other brands either change their channel distribution or reduce their channel distribution. And the great thing is that we have a very diversified portfolio of customer base. As you heard from George, department stores are only a segment of our retail and then we also do business with the mid-tiers where they change stores and mass as well as authentic golf channel. So we feel that there is definitely still white space opportunity and remember that we also have the growth of many of the new initiatives as we discussed on the call.
Greg Pendy
Okay, thanks. That's helpful. And then I guess just thinking about inventory turns. You said products moving -- I guess is hitting the shelves faster at retail. Just what your thoughts are about as the landscape for retail now, we're starting to see closures. Have you guys experienced any of those slower-moving store closures out there in the environment also aiding inventory turns at all, or is it too early to tell?
Oscar Feldenkreis
Well, we over the years -- retailers have been saying that their main focus is to make sure that they have the right assortment in their A&B doors and as well as the increase of online business has allowed us to ensure that the A&B doors are the doors that have the right assortment and the right level of inventory. Because other than the stores, really that turn inventory much more quicker than a CD et cetera level. So we're constantly analyzing our inventory in the actual stores and our weeks of supply to ensure that we're very fluid and be able to turn and reduce markdowns in the stores -- which at the end of the day, the higher your returns, the higher your sellthroughs, the less dilutions you have and the more productivity you can create in the stores.
Greg Pendy
Okay. Thanks. That's helpful.
George Feldenkreis
I also wanted to add, Oscar, that the retail, that our closing store are closing the worse stores and many of our products are not in those stores. Even when they are, those are the store that sell slowly the product and take big markdowns. In a way it might hit us in a 1% or 2% less sales, makes a penny or something like that. In reality, the markdowns probably will be less than what we lose on the revenue side.
Greg Pendy
Got it. Thanks.
Operator
And lastly, we'll go to Ed Yruma from KeyBanc Capital Markets.
Ed Yruma
Hi. Good morning. Thanks for squeezing me in. Anita, if you're listening, best of luck going forward. Just a couple of quick things, I think first on this revenue shift, I guess what disability do you have particularly to the back half revenue? Do you have orders in hand or I guess what percent of the book at this state is complete to give us confidence that this revenue will actually just shift towards to disappear?

Oscar Feldenkreis
We're in the process. I would say that the first half of the year has already been booked and we're in the process now of finalizing Q3. So we have definitely confidence that this would materialize and we also planned our revenue numbers for this year based on the expectations that the holiday season again will be dismal as it has been for the last couple of years has been the track record. If we have the ability to do better, we will have the inventory available to be able to do more but it's -- we're very conservative, we're very cautious and as interest rates go up, retail is a very concern and also making sure that their inventories are part to when the actual trends are needed.
Ed Yruma
Got it. And George, you mentioned kind of agility and speed of supply chain, I know you decided obviously the successes that some of the vertically oriented retailers are enjoying. I guess as you think about kind of speeding up the supply chain in the way you go to market, could you contextualize kind of how many days or weeks you could take out of the existing supply chain and how you can be maybe more responsive to this rapidly shifting order patterns? Thank you.
George Feldenkreis
Look, the partner stores, especially and some of the other retailers and system having sample of products before they play, therefore, they -- you see what Amazon is doing by not showing a sample of anything they sell, the consumer is now getting more and more used but on a digital way. We have now introduced totally new software that you can look at the garment and see how it moves around the body under 60 degree. So that will avoid the necessity in many, many cases, especially in the mens business of fits and making sure that it fits etcetera; because you see it on the screen, the designer sees it on the screen but they can make adjustment on the screen, this is number one. Number two is if the buyers would be able to buy from the digital presentation we had a number of our class win, such a presentation with one of our major customers and it was a trivially successful. Buyers come by from digital whereas I'm asking for sample. You can cut the production process by 1.5 to 2 months because in that sense other than the product that we make for our own stores etcetera, etcetera, not lies where we take the -- but we are actually taking the risk of the product.
Other than that when we do a business with -- I mean actually majority of our business, it's all done by showing example before if you got that process, you will be able to cut a 1.5 to 2 months of deliveries. So you will be able to -- for example, normally on the swim business, you study March designing and show samples in July [indiscernible]. Then the buyers ask you -- they come to a shore in July and then they ask you to place orders in September. September to be delivered in December/January. Now if you can design in June, you will actually know what sold this year in December. So when you're this time for next year, you will have a much better idea that you have in the month of March before this year season even happens. So those things are really delaying the process of making product in a fast way and making it to the consumers in a fast way.
Ed Yruma
Great, thanks so much.
Operator
With no further questions in the queue, I would like to turn the call back over to Mr. George Feldenkreis for any additional comments or closing remarks.
George Feldenkreis
Thank you. First of all, I want to take this opportunity to thank and interpret [ph] for a very important contribution to the growth and stability of this company. We are indebted to you Anita -- I'm sorry, for the great job you have done and we should be very best in your now future activities. I would like to thank all of our stockholders and annual shareholder and look forward to updating you on our start to fiscal 2018 after the first quarter. Have a great day.

Operator
Ladies and gentlemen, that does conclude our conference for today. Thank you all for your participation, you may now disconnect.
